did.abstract: The collection consists chiefly of the correspondence, writings, biographical materials, research files, photographs, and personal papers of librarian, curator and bibliophile Dorothy Porter Wesley. The bulk of the collection is comprised of research materials relating to various subjects pertaining to African American history, culture, and bibliography, including the following: African-American abolitionists Sarah Remond and William C. Nell, African American literature, African literature, and Afro-Brazilian literature. The collection also includes records of the Association for the Study of African-American Life and History.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Purchased from William Reese Co., (Swann African American sale, New York, 2012 March 1, lot 296) on the Sinclair Lewis Fund, 2012.

custodhist.head: Custodial History
custodhist.p: Materials were received directly from Swann Auction Galleries. The July 2012 addition, was received from the William Reese Co., after shipment from Florida where it had been found in storage by Wesley's family. The November 2012 addition was received from Swann Auction Galleries via the William Reese Co. after members of Wesley's family sent additional materials to Swann Auction Galleries.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: The collection is open for research.

This collection may be housed off-site at Yale's Library Shelving Facility (LSF). To determine if all or part of this collection is housed off-site please check the library's online catalog, Orbis; material for which the location is given as "LSF" must be requested 36 hours in advance. Please consult with Beinecke Access Services for more information.

bioghist.head: Dorothy Porter Wesley (1905-1995)
bioghist.p: Dorothy Burnett Porter Wesley (1905-1995) librarian, curator and bibliophile, was born on May 25, 1905 in Warrenton, Virginia to physician Hayes Joseph Burnett and tennis player Roberta ("Bertha") Ball Burnett. Wesley, the eldest of four children, grew up in Montclair, New Jersey. She graduated from Miner Normal School, Washington D.C. in 1925 with the intention of becoming a teacher. Wesley worked as a library assistant in the Miner Normal School library where she worked with librarian Lula V. Allan who encouraged her to pursue a career in library science. Wesley enrolled in Howard University in 1926 and received a BA in 1928. After graduation from Howard University in 1928, Wesley began work as a full-time librarian at Howard University. In 1928 Wesley enrolled at Colombia University's School of Library Science where Wesley received a Master's in Library Science in 1931. In 1930, Wesley began work as curator of the Moorland Foundation, now known as the Moorland-Spingarn Research Center, at Howard University and worked to build collections documenting the African diaspora until her retirement in 1973. Under Wesley's administration, the Moorland-Spingarn Research Center became a world-renowned institution for the history and culture of people of African descent. After retirement, Wesley worked as a consultant for Radcliffe University's Black Women Oral History Archive and authored several articles, and books pertaining to librarianship and the African diaspora. Books authored by Dorothy Porter Wesley include Early Negro Writing, 1760-1837 (1971), and Afro-Braziliana: A Working Bibliography (1978) . Wesley married artist and art history professor James Amos Porter (1905-1970) and had a daughter, Constance Porter Uzelac (1939-2012). After James Porter's death in 1970, she married former Wilberforce University president and African American historian, Charles Harris Wesley in 1979. Dorothy worked with Charles on a variety of projects including research for a bibliography on abolitionist William Cooper Nell until Charles's death in 1987. William Cooper Nell, Nineteenth-Century African American Abolitionist, Historian, Integrationist: Selected Writings 1832-1874 (2002) was later published by Constance Porter Uzelac in 2001. Dorothy Porter Wesley died in Broward County, Florida in 1995.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection consists chiefly of the correspondence, writings, biographical materials, research files, photographs, and personal papers of librarian, curator and bibliophile Dorothy Porter Wesley. The bulk of the collection is comprised of research materials relating to various subjects relating to African American history, culture, and bibliography, including the following: African-American abolitionists Sarah Remond and William C. Nell, African American literature, African literature, and Afro-Brazilian literature. The collection also includes records of the Association for the Study of Afro-American Life and History.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This collection is organized into four series: Series I. Correspondence, 1870-2011. Series II. Professional Papers, 1869-2003. Series III. Research Files, 1847-2004. Series IV. Personal Papers, 1869-2006.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Correspondence consists of letters to and from or indirectly received by Dorothy Porter Wesley and her family. The series documents Wesley's professional and personal activities as librarian and curator at the Moorland-Spingarn Research Center as well as her commitments as a consultant on the Black Women's Oral History Project at Radcliffe Institue, and in organizations such as The Association for the Study of African American Life and History, the National Council of Negro Women, Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc., and the W.E.B. Dubois Research Institute at Harvard University.

General Correspondence documents Wesley's professional activities, including her work with former Howard University president Mordecai Wyatt Johnson, sociologist Adelaide McGuinn Cromwell, John Wesley Blassingame, and authors Charles L. Blockson and Dorothy Sterling. Family Correspondence includes letters to and from Dorothy Porter Wesley as well as third-party subjects. Dorothy Porter Wesley's daughter Constance Porter Uzelac, and husbands James Amos Porter and Charles Harris Wesley are included in this series. Third Party Correspondence includes correspondence collected by Dorothy Porter Wesley during her lifetime.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is organized into three sub-series: General Correspondence; Family Correspondence; and Third Party Correspondence. Materials in each subseries are arranged alphabetically by last name and chronologically within folders.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Professional Papers is organized into three subseries: General; Speeches; and Writings.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Professional Papers consists of materials related to the professional career of Dorothy Porter Wesley. General files include memorandums, notes and writings from committees and organizations Wesley was a member of including the Association for the study of African American Life and History, the National Council of Negro Women, the African American Materials Project, Federal Writers Project, the Ford Foundation, and the National Endowment for the Humanities. Also included are records from Wesley's tenure as librarian and curator at the Moorland-Spingarn Research Center including reports, and correspondence documenting book orders used to build the collection.

Speeches document the lectures and remarks made by Wesley about librarianship and collections documenting the African Diaspora at universities such as Howard University, Boston University and Yale University. Writings consists of both published and unpublished bibliographies, essays, forewords and introductions on the subject of African, African American and Afro-Caribbean history and literature.It includes writings by Dorothy Porter Wesley James A. Porter, Charles H. Wesley, Constance Porter Uzelac; and a general assortment of writings by others.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Research Files is organized into five subseries: African Literature and Culture; African American Literature and Culture; Caribbean and South American Literature and Culture; Remond Family research; and William Cooper Nell research.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Research Files consists of clippings, drafts, photostat reprints of letters and notes documenting the research conducted by Dorothy Porter Wesley, Constance Porter Uzelac and Charles Harris Wesley. Materials include research on African, African American, Afro-Caribbean, and Afro-Latino literature and culture used for building the Moorland Spingarn Collection as well as Dorothy Porter Wesley's bibliographies, published books and articles including Afro-Braziliana: A Working Bibliography (1978) , Early Negro Writing, 1760-1837 (1971), and William Cooper Nell, Nineteenth-Century African American Abolitionist, Historian, Integrationist: Selected Writings 1832-1874 (2002) . Articles on Sarah Parker Remond, Charles Lenox Remond and their families written by Dorothy Porter Wesley are also included. Dorothy Porter Wesley's second husband, historian and author Charles Harris Wesley's notes and drafts for William Cooper Nell, Nineteenth-Century African American Abolitionist, Historian, Integrationist: Selected Writings 1832-1874 (2002) , are also contained in the series. Other writings include notes and illustrations by Constance Porter Uzelac who completed the bibliography on William Cooper Nell, Nineteenth-Century African American Abolitionist, Historian, Integrationist: Selected Writings 1832-1874 (2002) in 2002. The series also contains clippings, correspondence and writings on Alain Leroy Locke, professor at Howard University, as well as the correspondence and catalog books of Arthur Barnette Spingarn, who collected African American books, newspapers and manuscripts and whose collection formed the basis of the Moorland Spingarn Collection at Howard University.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Dorothy Porter Wesley visited West African countries such as Ghana, Nigeria, Senegal and the Ivory Coast to collect Africana materials for the Moorland-Spingarn Research Center. Wesley also worked as an acquisitions librarian at the National Library of Nigeria, a position she received as part of a Ford Foundation grant from 1962-1964. The African Literature and Culture research subseries consists of bibliographies, notes, clippings and articles documenting Wesley's experience in West Africa.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The African American Literature and Culture research subseries consists of clippings, notes, and writings documenting the research conducted by Dorothy Porter Wesley for collection development in the Moorland-Spingarn Research Center. The subseries contains materials about and belonging to writer, philospher and educator Alain Locke including correspondence and writings. Materials belonging to Civil Rights leader and collector Arthur Barnette Spingarn, including correpondence and book catalogs can also be found in the subseries. Research and drafts for Early Negro Writings, 1760-1837 (1971) written by Dorothy Porter Wesley is also included.

scopecontent.p: The Remond Family Papers consists of the research conducted by Dorothy Porter Wesley on the abolitionist Remond family of Salem, Massachusetts, specifically Sarah Parker Remond and Charles Lenox Remond. A majority of the subseries consist of articles, clippings and notes documenting the Remond family.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Personal Papers includes photographs, financial documents and ephemera belonging to Dorothy Porter Wesley, Constance Porter Uzelac, James Amos Porter, Charles Harris Wesley, and other extended family members. Dorothy Porter Wesley received personal items from her parents and siblings upon their deaths including tennis records, a memoir and records documenting the tennis career of Wesley's mother, Roberta (Bertha) Ball Burnett, and deeds and journals from her sisters Leonie Burnett Harper and Alice Taylor. Other items include original commencement records from Howard University School of Medicine and Lincoln University respectively belonging to Wesley's father Hayes Joseph Burnett and brother Hayes Burnett II. Wesley was also a beneficiary of the estate belonging to Lula V. Allan and Bertha Allan, who were librarians, teachers and mentors to Wesley at Miner Normal School. The materials belonging to Lula and Bertha Allan include third party correspondence, wills, photographs and ephemera.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Personal Papers is organized into five subseries: General Personal Papers belonging to Dorothy Porter Wesley; Financial records; Ephemera; Family Papers; and Lula and Bertha Allan papers.
